-- Adam Dray writes --
> This is what I'd call an inverse difficulty system.
>
> Character stats are numeric (rated 0 to some number).  Task difficulties are
> rated in terms of DICE -- an easy task might be rated "1d6" and a hard task
> might be rated "5d6".
>
> To resolve tasks, the dice described by the difficulty rating (e.g., 4d6) are
> rolled and compared to the skill or attribute stat.
>
> If the roll is equal to or less than the stat, the roll succeeds.  If the
> roll is more than the stat, the roll fails.
>
> I did some computer calculations to show you what the curves end up looking
> like for various skill levels and difficulty ratings:

    Ok, so this is good. I mean really good. I like the way it takes an old
method of resolution and turns things around a little. It might take a
little getting used to concept wise. I'm sure that most people could handle
rolling under their skill or attirbute score, but the idea of rolling
differnet numbers of dice for different levels of difficulty might need
some mental adjusting too.

> -------------------------------------------------
> NOTE: This chart would never be used in play; it
> is only here to show you the probability curves!
> -------------------------------------------------
> [Chart Sacrificed to the God of Bandwidth]

    Well, I suppose the only question I have about this so far, is how do
we control the increase of skills under this system? Would the player
always roll the highest number of dice (6d6) to see if a skill or attribute
increased? This is kind of a logical solution, since that is the only way
to increase a score beyond 30 to the maximum of 36, but if 36 is no the
maximum (still working for the open-ended system) then how do you decide
what to roll for skill increase?

>
